WEBVTT

00:00:01.720 --> 00:00:03.920
We need new voices.

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:05.600
Voices that can ask
the right questions.

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:07.920
[Host 1] How will
artificial intelligence change the world?

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:09.600
[Host 2]
The risks of artificial intelligence.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:10.400
[Host 3]
Artificial intelligence.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:11.400
[Host 4]
The big revolution.

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:12.800
[Host 5]
Supercomputers.

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:14.560
[Host 6]
Penetrating all fields.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:17.760
Voices that help us understand
the changing world around us.

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:20.080
Day by day,
and minute by minute.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:22.280
Voices that will
help us deal with

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.000
unprecedented
technological leaps.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:26.560
Artificial intelligence...

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:28.160
Machine learning...

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:30.560
Large language models...

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:32.000
What do they mean?

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:33.880
And how do we
navigate our new world

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:36.560
responsibly and ethically?

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:39.160
Voices that can
make sense of all the data

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:41.480
and measure its
effects on our lives.

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:44.280
Voices that
can spot trends,

00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:46.560
and point out
the gaps.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:48.480
Voices that represent us
in conversations,

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:50.800
locally and globally.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:52.560
A regional platform
for the Middle East

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:54.040
and North Africa.

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:55.440
Bringing together
policymakers,

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:57.880
researchers, civil society,
and people

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:00.840
who are passionate about
knowledge for everyone.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:02.920
We need voices
that can respond to

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:05.760
the most important
question we face today:

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:09.880
What does the future look like?

